## Simulation and benchmarking

`sim_scenario()` generates right-censored survival data from one of three
named scenarios with mixture-Weibull baseline hazards (bathtub, hump-shaped,
early peak). `mixWeibSc()` evaluates the corresponding true $h$, $H$, and $S$
on a grid for comparison with fitted estimates.

```{r simulate}
set.seed(42)
dat <- sim_scenario(scenario = 1, beta1 = 0.5, beta2 = 0.5, n = 500)
head(dat)
```

```{r fit}
fit <- fit_genhaz(
  surv       = Surv(dat$time, dat$event),
  formula    = ~ X,
  data       = dat,
  model_type = "GH",
  profile    = TRUE,
  n_knots    = 6,
  tol_LCV    = 0.05,
  lcv_method = "optimize"
)
```

```{r print}
print(fit)
```

### Inference

`waldCI()` computes a Wald CI for a single parameter; `waldCI_minus()` gives a
CI for $\beta_1 - \beta_2$ (accounting for their covariance).

```{r waldci}
waldCI(fit, "beta1_X")
waldCI(fit, "beta2_X")
waldCI_minus(fit, "beta1_X", "beta2_X")
```

Fit a restricted (PH) model and test against the full GH model:

```{r lr-test}
fit_ph <- fit_genhaz(
  surv       = Surv(dat$time, dat$event),
  formula    = ~ X,
  data       = dat,
  model_type = "PH",
  profile    = TRUE,
  n_knots    = 6,
  tol_LCV    = 0.05,
  lcv_method = "optimize"
)

LR(fit_ph, fit)
```

